pr_review_comment_body:
[Queue.__init__](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/master/Lib/multiprocessing/queues.py#L36) is defined like this:

    def __init__(self, maxsize=0, *, ctx):

And [multiprocessing/context.py](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/master/Lib/multiprocessing/context.py#L98) have some magic hide the detail that make you feel like ctx is not exists:

    def Queue(self, maxsize=0):
        '''Returns a queue object'''
        from .queues import Queue
        return Queue(maxsize, ctx=self.get_context())

But, you must get your hands dirty if you override Queue class (and others).

@awestendorf: I just noticed that the description doesn't match the implementation. The implementation appears to be that if user passed `heartbeat=None`, then the heartbeat value is broker-assigned; if user passed `heartbeat=0`, then heartbeats would be disabled. The description is the reverse of what actually happens.

```
        if self.connection._heartbeat is None:
            self.connection._heartbeat = method_frame.args.read_short()
```

Nice work!
By the way, Multiplies are a lot slower than adds, so you can get even faster by reducing the muls in the loop ( + and * replace by single +):
```cpp
const Dtype *batch_data_c = batch_data;
Dtype *top_data_c = top_data, *argmax_data_c = argmax_data; 
for (int c = 0; c < channels_; ++c) {
  // Increment all data pointers
  batch_data_c  += data_size_c;
  top_data_c    += out_size_c;
  argmax_data_c += max_idx_size_c;
  .
  .
  .
}
```

Likewise, this is *almost* the same as the plotselected function above, except for the last few lines.

You can do a similar strategy as above by defining a plotSelected function. To get the extra behaviour for the main graph event, do something like this:

```
$('#graph').bind("plotselected", function(event, ranges) {
  plotSelected(event, ranges);
  // Make overview graph display the selected range.
  $scope.plot.clearSelection();
  zoomGraph();
});

```python

@staticmethod
def _is_newer(this_timestamp, than_this_timestamp):
    return this_timestamp < than_this_timestamp

def _has_to_be_crawled(self, reques, spider):    
        request_db_key = self._get_key(request)

        if not request_db_key in self.db:
            return True

        new_request_timestamp = self._get_timestamp(request, spider)
        parsed_url = urlparse(request.url)
        if self._is_newer(
            new_request_timestamp,
            self.db.get(key=request_db_key),
        ):
                    return True

    return False

def process_request(self, request, spider):
    if not request.meta.get('crawl_once', self.default):
        return

    if not self._has_to_be_crawled(request, spider):
        self.stats.inc_value('crawl_once/ignored')
        raise IgnoreRequest()
```

It seems like this could be refactored to leverage the existing datetime_type method and avoid duplicating the logic here. You could merge these into one method with a parameter to toggle the behavior:

```Python
get_datetime_type_method(to_string=False):
   def datetime_type(string):
      # stuff goes here
      if to_string:
        return datetime.strptime(string, form).strftime(form)
     else:
        return datetime.strptime(string, form)
   return datetime_type
```

